http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Module of the Transmodel Ontology focused on Journeys

https://w3id.org/transmodel/journeys#des.@value: Module of the Transmodel Ontology focused on journeys. This ontology provides support to the NeTEx model. Visit https://github.com/oeg-upm/transmodel-ontology

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value:
The physical spatial possibility for a passenger to access or leave the public transport system. The link may be used during a Trip for:

- The walking movement of the Passenger from a Place (Origin of the Trip) to a ScheduledStopPoint (origin of the Public Transport Trip).
- The walking movement of the Passenger from a Scheduled Stop Point (destination of the Public Transport Trip) to a Place (destination of the Trip)
A characterisation of the passenger movement according to the means of transport different from public transport: walking, own bike,
A Zone for which the duration to cover any Access link to a particular ScheduledStopPoint is the same

The descriptive data associated with a Place that can be used to describe the unique geographical context of a Place for the purposes of identifying. May be refined as either a Road Address, a Postal Address or both.
An allowed direction that can be used on a given Route. This can be used to validate the selection of allowed values
A Point where a beacon or similar device to support the automatic detection of vehicles passing by is located

The work of a vehicle from the time it leaves a ParkingPoint after parking until its next retrun to park at a ParkingPoint. Any subsequent departure form a ParkingPoint after parking marks the start of a new Block. The period of a Block must be covered by Duties.
Part of a Block corresponding to the different JourneyPart of the VehicleJourney in a Block
A location within a Quay from which Passenger may directly board, or onto which passengers may directly alight from a Vehicle
The work of a vehicle during the time it is coupled to anohter vehicle

A complete journey operated by a coupled train, composed of two or more Vehicle Journeys remaining coupled together all along a Journey Pattern. A Coupled Journey may be viewed as a single VehicleJourney.
A part of a Block composed of consecutive VehicleJourneys defined for the same DayType, all operated on the same Line.
A DayType is a type of day characterised by one or more properties which affect public transport operation

Specialisation of Line for flexible service. As all the service on a Line may not ve flexible, flexibility itself is described at JourneyPattern level, meaning that a separate JourneyPattern is needed for each type of flexibility available for the line
A specialisation of Point for FlexibleService
Specialisation of Route for FlexibleService. May include both Point and Zonal areas and ordered and unordered sections.
A time interval or a duration defining a headway period and characterizing HeadwayJourneyGroup
A part of a VehicleJourney created according to a specific functional purpose, for instance in situations when Vehicle coupling or separating occurrs
Two JourneyParts of different VehicleJourneys served simultaneously by a train set up by coupling their single Vehicles

An ordered list of Scheduled Stop Points and Timing Point on a single Route, describing the pattern of working for public transport vehicles. A Journey Pattern may pass through the same Point more than once. The first point of a JourneyPattern is the origin. The last point is the destination.

A JourneyPatternLayover is the time allowance at the end of each journey on a specified JourneyPattern to allow for delays and for other purposes. This layover supersedes any global layover and may be superseded by a specific VehicleJourneyLayover
A Line is a group of Route which is generally known to the public by a similar name or number.
Any Mode of Transport
A day of public transport operation of which the characteristics are defined within in a specific ServiceCalendar. An OperatingDay may last more than 24 hours.
A ParkingPoint where vehicles may stay unattended for a long time. A vehicle's return to the ParkingPoint marks the end of a Block
A Passenger is someone who makes a Trip
A Point is a 0-dimensional Node of the Network used for the spatial description of the network. Point may be located by a Location

A specification of Address refining it by using the attributes used for conventional identification for mail. Comprises variously a building identifier, Streeet name, Post Code and other descriptions.
PostalAddress

A place where Passenger have access to Vehicles, taxi, cars or other means of transportation. A Quay may serve one or more VehicleStoppingPlace and be associated with one or more ScheduledStopPoints.

A Quay may contain a subquay.
Specialisation of Address refining it by using the characteristics such as road number and mname use for conventional inidentification of along a road
A Route is and ordered list of located Point defining one single path through the road (or rail) network.
A ScheduledStopPoint is a Point where a Passenger can board or alight from a Vehicle.

A ServiceJourney is a Passenger carrying VehicleJourney for one
specified DayType. The pattern of working is in principle defined
by a ServiceJourneyPattern.
The Journey Pattern for a passenger carrying Service Journey
A place comprising one or more locations where Vehicles may stop and where passengers may board or leave Vehicles or prepare their Trip. A StopPlace will usually have one or more wellknown names.
A Point in Journey Pattern that is a ScheduledStopPoint

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value:
A TimingLink is an ordered pair of TimingPoint for which run times
may be recorded.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value:
A TimingLinkInJourneyPattern is the position of a TimingLink in a
JourneyPattern. This entity is needed if a TimingLink is repeated
in the same JourneyPattern, and separate information is to be stored
about each iteration of the TimingLink

A TimingPoint is a Point against which the timing information necessary to build schedules may be recorded.

It's the same as TimingPointInJourneyPattern
A Point in a JourneyPattern which is a TimingPoint
The physical spatial possibility for a passenger to travel from a Place (located Point) origin of the Trip to another place (located Point) destination of the Trip.

TypeOfFlexibleService are:
-. Veritual line service
- Flexible service with main route
- Corridor service
- Fixed stop area-wide flexible service
- Free area-wide flexible service
- Mixed types of flexible service
- Mixed type of flexible and regular service
A PublicTransportVehicle used for carrying Passengers

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#lab.@value: The planned movement of a Public Transport Vehicle on a DayType from the start point to the end point of a JourneyPattern on a specified Route.

http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value:
A place on the vehicle track where vehicles stop in order for passengers to board or alight from a vehicle.

A vehicle track is located on the respective infrastructure link for the mode (railway element of railway network, road element of road network, etc.).

A vehicle stopping place may be served by one or more quays.
buildingIdentifier
Sequences of ScheduledStopPoint
The allocation of a ScheduledStopPoint (i.e. a ScheduledStopPoint of a ServicePattern or JourneyPattern) to a specific StopPlace, for either a ServiceJourney or VehicleService
Sequences of TimePoints
